If you need consular assistance contact the British High Commission in St Lucia.
Hurricane Beryl is approaching the Lower Antilles region and a Tropical Storm watch is now in place for St Lucia. You should monitor local media for updates, and follow the instructions of the local authorities. More information about Hurricane Beryl and its progress can be found at the National Hurricane Centre website or twitter page.
The hurricane season in the Caribbean normally runs from June to November. You can monitor weather updates from the US National Hurricane Center. See Natural disasters
UK health authorities have classified St Lucia as having a risk of Zika virus transmission. For information and advice about the risks associated with Zika virus, visit the National Travel Health Network and Centre website.
Cases of Chikungunya virus have been confirmed in St Lucia. You should take steps to avoid being bitten by mosquitoes.
Most visits are trouble-free, but there have been incidents of crime including murder, armed robbery and sexual assault. See Crime
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in St Lucia, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
